4:30 Itanian time. Cohren hated waking up so early. Especially since it was his responsibility to wake up all the other members of his company. Silently slipping out of his cot, he put on his combat uniform, buckled on his tactical vest, and gathered the items from his locker, paying particular attention to a small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and hung his helmet on a small hook attached to his belt. The helmet was fully equipped: breathing apparatus, goggles, and everything else needed. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly left the barracks, the sound of mud and crushed ice echoing under his boots.
He took out a lighter from the pocket of his vest and a cigarette from the other. As he lit it, he took a small puff before opening the door gently. Last week, he had had to be creative to wake up the men and women under his command. He had stopped using the preset alarm clock; half the time it didn't work anyway, as whatever came out of the speakers was just a faint whistle.
"Are you waking them up?" Cohren turned around to see Second Lieutenant Nemic approaching.
"Yes," replied Cohren.
"The next time, what are you planning to use?"
Before he could respond, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and other soldiers rushed out, already dressed and equipped.
"Hello," said Craith.
"what woke you up?" asked Cohren.
Well, first of all, we didn't want to see what you had planned for us to wake us up today. Second, the first shock troops awake are the first to breakfast. One of them, Ravik, replied: "And you know how bad it can be."
"You score a point, Specialist," said Cohren. He reached out and activated a switch. An alarm began to blare loudly inside the barracks. He heard commotion and noise coming from within.
"Christ, Valturi," launched Nemic. "One would think they could have learned to get up at the same time as you by now."
"Well, my training camp buddies here did it," Cohren turned to Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "But again, their team and section leaders know to rise before their units."
A few seconds later, the rest of the company poured out en masse. Everyone had what they needed, from personal items to the necessary equipment. Some of the new recruits looked disoriented, while others seemed more irritated.
"Hello everyone," said Cohren with an enthusiastic voice.
"Except for your respect, sir, why are you insisting on waking us up in this manner?" asked one of the shock troop members, a corporal.
"Because standard alarms are shit. And because Daybreak doesn't hit the snooze button," Cohren replied.
